s($,"b2R","aMR",()=>{var q="Basics",p="Beginner",o="Price Action",n="Intermediate",m="Risk",l="Psychology",k="Strategy",j="Execution",i="Review",h="Advanced"
return A.b([A.ah("A market is a place where value is exchanged. Price changes when demand and supply shift.",p,6,1,q,"Understand how markets move.","Learn how buyers and sellers set price.","Price reflects balance between buyers and sellers.","What is a market?"),A.ah("Charts show historical price action. Traders use them to spot direction, momentum, and structure.",p,7,2,q,"Read simple price charts.","See how data becomes a trading tool.","A chart is a visual record of price behavior.","What is a chart?"),A.ah("Each candlestick summarizes one period. The body shows open and close, while wicks show extremes.",p,8,3,q,"Interpret candle bodies and wicks.","Open, high, low, and close.","Candles reveal sentiment in each period.","Candlestick anatomy"),A.ah("An uptrend makes higher highs and higher lows. A downtrend makes lower highs and lower lows.",p,8,4,q,"Identify the market direction.","Uptrend, downtrend, and sideways movement.","Trend direction is the foundation of analysis.","Trends 101"),A.ah("Support is an area where buying appears. Resistance is an area where selling appears.",p,9,5,q,"Mark key reaction zones.","Where price often reacts.","Important levels often repeat reactions.","Support and resistance"),A.ah("Price action focuses on the movement itself instead of heavy indicators. Traders look for structure, momentum, and reaction to levels.",n,10,6,o,"Understand raw price movement.","Read the story behind every candle.","The cleanest signal is often the price itself.","Price action basics"),A.ah("A breakout happens when price moves beyond a key level or range. Good breakouts often come with strong volume and follow-through.",n,10,7,o,"Spot breakout setups.","When price leaves a range.","Not every breakout is real; confirmation matters.","Breakouts"),A.ah("A pullback is a short counter-move inside a larger trend. Traders often wait for pullbacks to enter with lower risk.",n,9,8,o,"Find better entry points.","A temporary move against the trend.","Trend pullbacks can offer cleaner entries.","Pullbacks"),A.ah("A false breakout happens when price briefly crosses a level but quickly returns. These moves trap impatient traders.",n,11,9,o,"Avoid weak entries.","When price tricks the crowd.","Wait for acceptance, not just a spike.","False breakouts"),A.ah("Structure shows whether the market is trending or reversing. It is built from swing highs and swing lows.",n,12,10,o,"Read market structure clearly.","Higher highs and lower lows.","Structure helps you understand trend and risk.","Price structure"),A.ah("Risk management is the process of limiting losses so one bad trade does not damage your account.",p,8,11,m,"Understand why risk control matters.","Protect capital first.","Survival comes before profit.","Risk management basics"),A.ah("Position sizing controls how much capital is exposed on each trade. Small, consistent risk is easier to manage.",p,9,12,m,"Size trades consistently.","Choose the right trade size.","Your size should match your stop loss.","Position sizing"),A.ah("A stop loss closes a trade when price proves the idea wrong. It should be placed where your setup is invalidated.",p,10,13,m,"Place stops logically.","Define your invalidation point.","A stop should protect the thesis, not just the account.","Stop loss placement"),A.ah("Risk to reward compares how much you can lose to how much you can gain. It helps you choose trades with positive expectancy.",n,10,14,m,"Compare downside to upside.","Measure the trade before entering.","Good trades should pay more than they risk.","Risk to reward"),A.ah("Drawdown is the decline from a peak in account equity. Keeping drawdown small helps preserve confidence and capital.",n,11,15,m,"Reduce damage during rough periods.","Handle losing streaks wisely.","Big drawdowns are harder to recover from.","Drawdown control"),A.ah("Discipline means executing your rules every time, even when you feel pressure, boredom, or fear.",p,8,16,l,"Build consistency.","Follow the plan even when emotions rise.","Discipline turns rules into results.","Trader discipline"),A.ah("Fear can make you exit too early. Greed can make you hold too long or overtrade.",p,9,17,l,"Recognize emotional bias.","Two emotions that distort decisions.","Strong emotions should not control entries or exits.","Fear and greed"),A.ah("Patience means letting the market come to your setup. Many traders fail because they trade too often.",p,9,18,l,"Avoid forcing trades.","Wait for the right setup.","No trade is also a decision.","Patience in trading"),A.ah("Losses are part of trading. The goal is to learn from them without changing your system emotionally.",n,10,19,l,"Recover emotionally after loss.","Stay steady after a bad trade.","A loss is feedback, not a verdict.","Dealing with losses"),A.ah("A trading journal records setup, entry, exit, emotions, and outcome. It helps identify patterns in behavior.",n,11,20,l,"Review decisions objectively.","Track what you did and why.","What gets tracked can improve.","Journaling trades"),A.ah("A strategy is a set of conditions for entering, managing, and exiting trades.",p,8,21,k,"Understand strategy structure.","A repeatable edge with rules.","A strategy should be simple and testable.","What is a trading strategy?"),A.ah("Trend following tries to capture sustained moves by entering in the direction of the dominant trend.",p,9,22,k,"Recognize trend-based systems.","Trade in the direction of momentum.","The trend is often your friend.","Trend following"),A.ah("Mean reversion strategies look for price extremes and aim for a move back toward a mean or average.",n,10,23,k,"Understand reversal-style setups.","Expect price to return to average.","Extremes often do not last forever.","Mean reversion"),A.ah("Breakout strategies attempt to join strong moves after price leaves consolidation.",n,11,24,k,"Use breakout rules safely.","Enter when price escapes a range.","Breakout success depends on confirmation and risk control.","Breakout strategy"),A.ah("Backtesting checks how a strategy would have performed in past market conditions.",n,12,25,k,"Validate a trading idea.","Test your idea on historical data.","A strategy should be tested before it is trusted.","Backtesting"),A.ah("Different order types help you control how and when you enter or exit the market.",p,8,26,j,"Know how to place trades.","Market, limit, and stop orders.","The right order type supports the plan.","Order types"),A.ah("Slippage happens when the fill price is worse or better than expected, often during fast moves.",n,9,27,j,"Understand execution risk.","When execution differs from expectation.","Fast markets can change execution quality.","Slippage"),A.ah("Liquidity is the amount of available buying and selling interest. Higher liquidity usually means smoother execution.",n,9,28,j,"Read market conditions better.","How easily price can move.","Low liquidity can increase spread and slippage.","Liquidity"),A.ah("Good timing means waiting for the conditions in your plan rather than entering too early.",n,10,29,j,"Improve entry discipline.","Choose a precise moment to act.","Good timing comes from patience.","Entry timing"),A.ah("Trade management includes moving stops, taking partial profits, and reacting to price without emotional noise.",n,11,30,j,"Manage open trades with logic.","Handle an open position properly.","Management should follow predefined rules.","Trade management"),A.ah("Trade review helps you see what worked, what failed, and whether you followed your plan.",p,8,31,i,"Start reviewing performance.","Learn from each finished trade.","Review turns experience into improvement.","Trade review basics"),A.ah("A mistake is something you control, like early entry or oversized risk. Market movement itself is not a mistake.",p,9,32,i,"Spot repeat problems.","Separate process errors from market noise.","Fix what you control.","Identify mistakes"),A.ah("Expectancy measures how much a strategy tends to earn or lose over many trades.",n,10,33,i,"Think in long-term outcomes.","Build a system that can grow over time.","Small edges repeated often can compound.","Improving expectancy"),A.ah("Consistency means the same setup, same size, and same process across multiple trades.",n,10,34,i,"Track trading consistency.","Measure how well you follow your rules.","Consistency is more important than excitement.","Consistency tracking"),A.ah("A routine helps you prepare, analyze, execute, and review with less emotional friction.",n,11,35,i,"Create a repeatable process.","Create a daily trading workflow.","Routine reduces chaos.","Building a routine"),A.ah("Advanced structure analysis looks at multiple swings, failed moves, and shift in market behavior.",h,12,36,h,"Analyze structure more precisely.","Read deeper price behavior.","Structure changes often before the crowd notices.","Advanced market structure"),A.ah("Confluence means several independent factors support the same trade idea, such as trend, level, and momentum.",h,11,37,h,"Use stronger trade confirmation.","When multiple signals agree.","More agreement can improve confidence.","Confluence"),A.ah("Multi-timeframe analysis checks trend and structure on larger and smaller charts to improve context.",h,12,38,h,"Align higher and lower timeframes.","View the market from several angles.","Higher timeframe context matters.","Multi-timeframe analysis"),A.ah("Different market sessions can bring different volatility, liquidity, and trade opportunities.",h,10,39,h,"Understand time-based behavior.","Know when activity changes.","Time of day can affect price action.","Market sessions"),A.ah("A trading plan defines what you trade, when you trade, how much you risk, and how you review results.",h,13,40,h,"Create a complete plan.","Put your rules into one clear system.","A clear plan reduces random decisions.","Trading plan design"),A.ah("Volatility describes how much and how quickly price changes. High volatility usually means wider swings.",p,8,41,q,"Understand market speed.","Measure how fast price moves.","Volatility changes risk and opportunity.","What is volatility?"),A.ah("Volume shows how many transactions or units were traded during a period. Strong moves often need strong participation.",p,8,42,q,"Use volume as context.","See how much participation is behind a move.","Volume can confirm price behavior.","What is volume?"),A.ah("A market order executes right away at the best available price. It is useful when speed matters more than exact price.",p,7,43,q,"Use fast execution when needed.","Enter immediately at the current price.","Fast execution can cost precision.","Market orders"),A.ah("A limit order waits for the market to reach your chosen price. It gives more control but may not fill.",p,7,44,q,"Control entry price better.","Set your preferred price.","Limit orders trade speed for price control.","Limit orders"),A.ah("A stop order activates when price reaches a specified level. Traders use it to enter breakouts or protect positions.",p,7,45,q,"Understand trigger-based entries.","Trigger a trade after price moves.","Stops can be used for entries or exits.","Stop orders"),A.ah("In a range, price moves between a ceiling and floor. Traders often buy support and sell resistance.",n,10,46,o,"Recognize sideways markets.","Trade between support and resistance.","Ranges reward patience and precision.","Range trading"),A.ah("Continuation setups aim to enter after a pause, expecting the existing trend to resume.",n,10,47,o,"Spot continuation setups.","Join a move that keeps going.","A pause is not always a reversal.","Trend continuation"),A.ah("A reversal happens when a trend loses strength and price begins moving in the opposite direction.",n,11,48,o,"Identify turning points.","When direction changes.","Reversals need evidence, not guesses.","Reversals"),A.ah("Swings are the visible waves in price movement. They help define structure, trend, and entry zones.",n,10,49,o,"Read swing highs and lows.","The push and pull of price.","Swings show the rhythm of the market.","Market swings"),A.ah("Momentum is the speed and persistence of a move. Strong momentum often appears as strong candles and follow-through.",n,10,50,o,"Measure the pace of price changes.","Gauge the strength behind a move.","Momentum helps judge whether a move is healthy.","Reading momentum"),A.ah("Capital preservation means focusing on avoiding large losses so you can stay in the game long term.",p,8,51,m,"Protect trading capital.","Keep your account alive.","Preserve capital before chasing growth.","Capital preservation"),A.ah("A daily loss limit prevents emotional revenge trading after a bad start.",p,8,52,m,"Set a hard stop for the day.","Know when to stop trading.","Stopping early can save the account.","Daily loss limit"),A.ah("Scaling in means adding to a trade in stages when the setup develops as expected.",n,10,53,m,"Understand controlled expansion.","Add to a position carefully.","Adding size should follow a plan.","Scaling in"),A.ah("Scaling out means closing part of a trade at one target and leaving some open for further movement.",n,10,54,m,"Manage exits more flexibly.","Take profits in parts.","Partial profits can reduce pressure.","Scaling out"),A.ah("A breakeven stop moves the stop loss to the entry price after the trade moves in your favor.",n,9,55,m,"Protect capital on winning trades.","Remove downside after progress.","Breakeven can reduce risk, but timing matters.","Breakeven stops"),A.ah("Healthy confidence comes from preparation and evidence, not from one lucky trade.",p,8,56,l,"Stay balanced mentally.","Trust your process, not your ego.","Trust the process, not the feeling.","Confidence without arrogance"),A.ah("FOMO is the fear of missing out. It often leads to poor entries and oversized risk.",p,8,57,l,"Stop emotional chasing.","Avoid chasing missed moves.","Missing one move is better than forcing a bad one.","Handling FOMO"),A.ah("Overtrading happens when you take too many low-quality setups, often out of boredom or emotion.",n,9,58,l,"Reduce unnecessary trades.","Too many trades, too little quality.","Activity is not the same as progress.","Overtrading"),A.ah("A reset routine can help after stress, loss, or a strong win so you do not carry emotion into the next trade.",n,9,59,l,"Return to a calm state.","Reset after intense trading.","Reset before the next decision.","Emotional recovery"),A.ah("Mental resilience is the ability to stay composed during losses, uncertainty, and slow progress.",n,10,60,l,"Become more stable under pressure.","Stay steady through uncertainty.","Resilience is trained through repetition.","Building mental resilience"),A.ah("An edge is any repeatable advantage that gives a strategy positive long-term expectation.",p,8,61,k,"Understand what makes a system work.","Find your statistical advantage.","Without edge, consistency is hard to sustain.","Edge in trading"),A.ah("Filters help you avoid low-quality trades by requiring extra conditions before entry.",n,9,62,k,"Improve setup quality.","Only take the best setups.","Fewer trades can mean better trades.","Trade filters"),A.ah("Confirmation is additional evidence that increases the chance a setup is valid.",n,9,63,k,"Reduce false signals.","Wait for proof before acting.","Confirmation can improve discipline.","Entry confirmation"),A.ah("An exit plan defines profit targets, stop placement, and the conditions for manual exit.",n,10,64,k,"Plan exits in advance.","Know how you will leave the trade.","Good exits are decided before entry.","Exit planning"),A.ah("A trading edge should be reviewed regularly to ensure market conditions have not changed too much.",h,12,65,k,"Evaluate strategy quality over time.","Check whether the edge still exists.","An edge can weaken if the market evolves.","Trading edge review"),A.ah("A structure shift happens when the sequence of highs and lows changes in a meaningful way.",h,11,66,j,"Spot shifts earlier.","Notice when the market changes character.","Character changes often lead price changes.","Market structure shift"),A.ah("Order flow examines how aggressive buying and selling move price through the market.",h,12,67,j,"Read pressure behind movement.","Understand buying and selling pressure.","Pressure can matter as much as direction.","Order flow basics"),A.ah("Alerts notify you when price reaches a key level or condition, helping you act with more patience.",p,7,68,j,"Avoid staring at charts all day.","Let the market come to you.","Alerts support discipline and timing.","Using alerts"),A.ah("Screening helps you search multiple markets or charts for the best opportunities.",n,9,69,j,"Filter the market efficiently.","Find candidates faster.","A good screen saves time.","Screening setups"),A.ah("A checklist helps you verify trend, setup, risk, and timing before entering a trade.",n,9,70,j,"Improve decision quality.","Use a simple before-trade checklist.","Checklists reduce preventable mistakes.","Trade checklist"),A.ah("Post-trade analysis checks the quality of the setup, execution, and management after the trade ends.",p,8,71,i,"Learn from finished trades.","Look at what actually happened.","Analysis should be honest and specific.","Post-trade analysis"),A.ah("Win rate is the percentage of trades that finish in profit. It is useful, but not the only important metric.",p,8,72,i,"Know your hit rate.","Measure how often your trades succeed.","Win rate matters, but expectancy matters more.","Tracking win rate"),A.ah("Expectancy combines win rate and average win/loss to estimate the long-term quality of a strategy.",n,10,73,i,"Understand strategy performance.","Measure average result per trade.","A positive expectancy is a powerful sign.","Tracking expectancy"),A.ah("Common mistakes include overtrading, moving stops too soon, and entering without a plan.",p,8,74,i,"Recognize recurring errors.","Spot the patterns that hurt performance.","Most problems repeat in patterns.","Common trading mistakes"),A.ah("An improvement loop is a cycle of testing, reviewing, and refining one part of your process.",n,10,75,i,"Improve systematically.","Make one adjustment at a time.","Small changes are easier to validate.","Improvement loops"),A.ah("Market context includes trend, volatility, session, and recent behavior that can influence your trade.",h,11,76,h,"Interpret the environment better.","Understand the bigger picture.","Context changes how you interpret signals.","Market context"),A.ah("A few wins can make traders careless. Consistent process matters more than a short lucky streak.",h,10,77,h,"Stay realistic after wins.","Avoid overestimating a recent streak.","Short-term success can be misleading.","False confidence"),A.ah("Scaling means increasing size or frequency only after a strategy proves stable over time.",h,11,78,h,"Expand carefully.","Grow only when the process is stable.","Growth should follow evidence.","Scaling a strategy"),A.ah("Adaptive traders change tactics when the market environment changes, while keeping core risk rules intact.",h,10,79,h,"Stay flexible when needed.","Adjust to changing conditions.","Flexibility is useful when markets evolve.","Adaptive thinking"),A.ah("Trading progress comes from many small improvements repeated over time.",h,12,80,h,"Think in years, not days.","Build skill step by step.","Progress is built, not found.","Long-term progression"),A.ah("Some sessions move fast, while others stay quiet. Knowing that helps you choose the right tactic.",h,10,81,h,"Match strategy to session behavior.","Learn how different hours affect movement.","Different sessions need different expectations.","Session volatility"),A.ah("The market open often brings a burst of volatility and sharp moves as liquidity and orders enter quickly.",h,10,82,h,"Read early-session action.","Watch the first minutes closely.","Open behavior can be unpredictable.","Market open behavior"),A.ah("News can create sudden volatility, spreads, and slippage. Traders should know when major events are scheduled.",h,10,83,h,"Prepare for event risk.","Understand how headlines move price.","News can override technical setups.","News impact"),A.ah("Correlation shows whether two markets tend to move in the same direction or in opposite directions.",h,11,84,h,"Avoid hidden overlap risk.","See how markets move together.","Correlated trades can increase exposure.","Correlation"),A.ah("Portfolio thinking considers how multiple positions interact so the overall risk stays controlled.",h,12,85,h,"Think about total account risk.","Look beyond one trade.","A group of trades is one risk picture.","Portfolio thinking"),A.ah("A repeatable process helps you reduce randomness by using the same rules and steps every time.",n,10,86,h,"Standardize your approach.","Build a system you can follow daily.","Repeatability creates consistency.","Repeatable process"),A.ah("Decision fatigue happens when many choices reduce mental energy and quality of judgment.",n,9,87,h,"Make better decisions longer.","Protect your focus over the day.","Fewer choices can improve performance.","Decision fatigue"),A.ah("The trading environment determines which setups are most likely to work well.",h,11,88,h,"Choose the right style.","Adapt to trending, ranging, or volatile markets.","Strategy should match environment.","Trading environment"),A.ah("Risk allocation is the process of deciding how much exposure each trade or idea should receive.",h,11,89,h,"Distribute risk intentionally.","Decide where your capital should go.","Not every setup deserves the same size.","Risk allocation"),A.ah("Performance review looks at results, behavior, and consistency across a large sample of trades.",h,12,90,h,"Understand your growth objectively.","Measure the full picture over time.","Long-term review is more useful than one trade.","Reviewing performance"),A.ah("Conviction grows when your strategy is tested and repeated enough to show a stable pattern.",h,10,91,h,"Gain confidence through data.","Trust your edge with evidence.","Evidence builds confidence.","Building conviction"),A.ah("Revenge trading usually increases risk and worsens losses after frustration.",h,9,92,h,"Prevent emotional damage.","Do not try to win it back immediately.","Walk away before emotion takes over.","Avoiding revenge trading"),A.ah("Simple systems are often easier to follow, test, and improve than complicated ones.",h,10,93,h,"Value clarity over complexity.","Complexity is not always better.","Simple rules are easier to execute.","Simple systems"),A.ah("Refinement means making small improvements while avoiding the temptation to optimize every detail.",h,11,94,h,"Refine without overfitting.","Improve one part at a time.","Small refinements are usually safer.","Strategy refinement"),A.ah("A strategy should be judged on a large enough sample so random luck does not distort the result.",h,12,95,h,"Evaluate properly.","Use enough trades before judging.","Big samples give better answers.","Long sample testing"),A.ah("Your behavior under pressure reveals whether your process is truly stable.",h,10,96,h,"Improve emotional control.","See how you react when it matters.","Pressure exposes weak spots.","Behavior under pressure"),A.ah("System confidence comes from a tested process and consistent execution over time.",h,10,97,h,"Build stable decision-making.","Trust the rules you have tested.","Confidence should come from proof.","System confidence"),A.ah("Overoptimization makes a system look good on old data but weak in new conditions.",h,11,98,h,"Keep strategies robust.","Do not fit your system too closely to the past.","A robust strategy is better than a perfect backtest.","Avoiding overoptimization"),A.ah("A professional mindset focuses on process, risk, and repeatability rather than excitement or prediction.",h,10,99,h,"Adopt a long-term mindset.","Think like a professional.","Think in probabilities, not certainty.","Trader mindset"),A.ah("Successful trading combines market reading, risk control, emotional discipline, and a repeatable process.",h,13,100,h,"Connect all trading concepts.","Combine analysis, risk, and discipline.","Results come from the whole system, not one idea.","Putting it all together")],t.Lo)})
